[2026-03-13T19:20:33Z] [llm] {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01BStR4S6RQXes4iLADK4rBV","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_019x5XjCDxncT8udAeAsAD6S","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/workspace/docs/workflows.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":7,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6585,"cache_read_input_tokens":12698,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":6585,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01H2TvBVQzYEZLZT535z7eqf","session_id":"5888bf68-422b-4315-97ee-07c9cf3aacfd","uuid":"5f6b27a0-4f5d-47f3-a475-0224598e01a4"}
[2026-03-13T19:20:33Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WCzm6PmtQ74mXq6D8QkDaT","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Cloche System Design\n     2→\n     3→## Overview\n     4→\n     5→Cloche is a system for grow-coding high quality applications. It provides containerized\n     6→environments for coding agents to operate in isolation, a workflow DSL for linking\n     7→agentic and script-driven tasks, validated code pipelines, and self-evolving tooling.\n     8→\n     9→This document describes the architecture for the MVP (v0.1).\n    10→\n    11→## System Components\n    12→\n    13→Cloche is a Go monorepo producing three binaries:\n    14→\n    15→```\n    16→cmd/\n    17→  cloche/         # CLI client (short-lived)\n    18→  cloched/        # Daemon/orchestrator (long-running)\n    19→  cloche-agent/   # In-container entrypoint (autonomous)\n    20→```\n    21→\n    22→### cloche (CLI)\n    23→\n    24→Short-lived process. Talks to `cloched` over gRPC (Unix socket locally, TCP remotely).\n    25→\n    26→Subcommands:\n    27→- `run <workflow>` — Launch a new workflow run\n    28→- `status [run-id]` — Check run status\n    29→- `logs <run-id>` — Stream logs from a running workflow (bidirectional gRPC stream)\n    30→- `stop <run-id>` — Cancel a running workflow (signals container with SIGTERM)\n    31→\n    32→Accepts prompt files or stdin input for user commands.\n    33→\n    34→### cloched (Daemon)\n    35→\n    36→Long-running process. Responsibilities:\n    37→- Launch and manage Docker containers for workflow runs\n    38→- Listen to status streams from running agents\n    39→- Record captures (step inputs, outputs, results, logs)\n    40→- Expose gRPC API for the CLI\n    41→- Persist state via pluggable storage (SQLite initially)\n    42→\n    43→The daemon does NOT interpret workflow logic. It knows \"container X is running workflow Y\"\n    44→and collects status. The agent is self-directing.\n    45→\n    46→### cloche-agent (In-Container Runtime)\n    47→\n    48→Autonomous process running inside the Docker container. Responsibilities:\n    49→- Parse the workflow DSL (workflow files live in the codebase)\n    50→- Walk the workflow graph, executing steps and following results\n    51→- Invoke coding agents (Claude Code, custom commands) and scripts\n    52→- Stream structured status events back to `cloched`\n    53→- Run to completion (`done` or `abort`) without human intervention\n    54→\n    55→The agent is told which workflow to execute at launch. It handles everything else.\n    56→\n    57→## Communication\n    58→\n    59→### CLI <-> Daemon: gRPC\n    60→\n    61→- Protobuf contracts define the API (the API is the spec)\n    62→- Bidirectional streaming for `logs` (tail container output in real-time)\n    63→- Unix socket for local communication, TCP for remote\n    64→\n    65→### Agent <-> Daemon: Structured JSON over stdout\n    66→\n    67→- The agent writes JSON-lines to stdout with status updates\n    68→- `cloched` attaches to the container's stdout stream via Docker API\n    69→- Messages include: step started, step completed (with result name), logs, errors\n    70→- Kill/cancel: daemon sends SIGTERM to container, agent handles graceful shutdown\n    71→\n    72→## Workflow DSL\n    73→\n    74→### Vocabulary\n    75→\n    76→| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    77→|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    78→| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    79→| step     | A unit of work (type: `agent` or `script`)                         |\n    80→| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n    81→| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step                              |\n    82→| done     | Built-in terminal step indicating successful completion            |\n    83→| abort    | Built-in terminal step indicating failure (reports error and exits)|\n    84→\n    85→### Syntax\n    86→\n    87→```\n    88→workflow \"implement-feature\" {\n    89→  step code {\n    90→    prompt = file(\"prompts/implement.md\")\n    91→    container {\n    92→      image = \"cloche/agent:latest\"\n    93→      network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\", \"internal-docs.company.com\"]\n    94→    }\n    95→    results = [success, fail, retry_with_feedback]\n    96→  }\n    97→\n    98→  step check {\n    99→    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n   100→    results = [pass, fail]\n   101→  }\n   102→\n   103→  step review {\n   104→    prompt = file(\"prompts/review.md\")\n   105→    input = step.code.output\n   106→    results = [approved, changes_requested]\n   107→  }\n   108→\n   109→  code:success -> check\n   110→  code:fail -> abort\n   111→  code:retry_with_feedback -> code\n   112→\n   113→  check:pass -> review\n   114→  check:fail -> code:retry_with_feedback\n   115→\n   116→  review:approved -> done\n   117→  review:changes_requested -> code\n   118→}\n   119→```\n   120→\n   121→### Key Properties\n   122→\n   123→- Step type is inferred from content: `prompt` field → agent step, `run` field → script step.\n   124→- Steps declare which results they can emit. The step decides at runtime which result to report.\n   125→- Wiring is separate from step definitions. This enables runtime injection of new steps\n   126→  (the self-evolution feature) — insert a new check between existing steps by rewiring,\n   127→  without modifying either step.\n   128→- `file()` loads external content (prompt files, scripts).\n   129→- Step inputs can reference other step outputs (`step.code.output`).\n   130→- The graph engine validates at parse time: all declared results are wired, no orphan steps,\n   131→  entry point exists.\n   132→\n   133→## Hexagonal Architecture\n   134→\n   135→The core domain is independent of Docker, gRPC, SQLite, or any other infrastructure.\n   136→\n   137→### Domain\n   138→\n   139→```\n   140→internal/domain/\n   141→  workflow.go    # Workflow, Step, Result, Graph types\n   142→  run.go         # Run, RunState, StepExecution types\n   143→  capture.go     # CapturedInput, CapturedOutput for replay\n   144→```\n   145→\n   146→### Ports (interfaces)\n   147→\n   148→```\n   149→internal/ports/\n   150→  store.go       # RunStore, WorkflowStore, CaptureStore\n   151→  container.go   # ContainerRuntime (start, stop, attach, logs)\n   152→  agent.go       # AgentAdapter (how to invoke an agent)\n   153→  notifier.go    # StatusNotifier (how to report progress)\n   154→```\n   155→\n   156→### Adapters (implementations)\n   157→\n   158→```\n   159→internal/adapters/\n   160→  docker/        # ContainerRuntime via Docker API\n   161→  sqlite/        # Store implementations via SQLite\n   162→  grpc/          # gRPC server (daemon) and client (CLI)\n   163→  agents/\n   164→    claudecode/  # AgentAdapter for Claude Code\n   165→    generic/     # AgentAdapter for arbitrary commands\n   166→```\n   167→\n   168→### Key Interfaces\n   169→\n   170→- **ContainerRuntime** — Start/stop containers, attach to stdout, copy files in/out.\n   171→  Docker today, Podman or Firecracker later.\n   172→- **RunStore** — Persist run state (active step, reported results, timestamps).\n   173→- **CaptureStore** — Store step inputs/outputs for replay. Git refs serve as pointers\n   174→  to file states; metadata lives in the store.\n   175→- **AgentAdapter** — Translates between Cloche's step protocol and a specific agent's\n   176→  interface. Claude Code adapter knows how to invoke `claude` CLI. Generic adapter runs\n   177→  any command.\n   178→- **StatusNotifier** — How the agent reports progress. Stdout JSON-lines initially.\n   179→\n   180→## Container Model\n   181→\n   182→### One Container Per Workflow Run\n   183→\n   184→A container is spun up for a workflow run. All steps execute inside the same container.\n   185→File state accumulates naturally across steps (agent modifies code, then test script\n   186→runs against those modifications).\n   187→\n   188→### Lifecycle\n   189→\n   190→1. `cloched` pulls/builds the container image\n   191→2. Copies project files into the container at `/workspace`\n   192→3. Starts the container with `cloche-agent` as entrypoint, passing the workflow name\n   193→4. `cloche-agent` parses the workflow, walks the graph, executes steps\n   194→5. Agent streams status events to `cloched` via stdout\n   195→6. At step boundaries, modified files are pushed to the host via git (agent-specific branch)\n   196→7. On completion (`done`/`abort`), container is stopped\n   197→\n   198→### File Extraction via Git\n   199→\n   200→The container's git remote is configured to push to the host repository. Each run pushes\n   201→to a unique branch (e.g. `cloche/run-<id>/step-<name>`). This provides:\n   202→- Full git history of what the agent did\n   203→- Trivial diffs between input and output states\n   204→- Clean branch-per-step organization\n   205→- No bind mounts (maintains isolation)\n   206→\n   207→### Security Boundaries\n   208→\n   209→1. **Filesystem** — No access beyond `/workspace`. Copy-in at start, git push for extraction.\n   210→2. **Network** — `--network none` by default. If `network_allow` is specified, Cloche creates\n   211→   a custom Docker network restricting egress to allowlisted domains via DNS proxy.\n   212→3. **Environment** — Configured in Dockerfile/image. Cloche does not inject env vars.\n   213→\n   214→## Capture System\n   215→\n   216→Each step execution is captured for later inspection and replay.\n   217→\n   218→### What Gets Captured\n   219→\n   220→- Step config (prompt, type, container settings)\n   221→- Input state (git ref of what was provided to the step)\n   222→- Output state (git ref of what the step produced)\n   223→- Result reported (which result name)\n   224→- Stdout/stderr logs\n   225→- Timing metadata\n   226→\n   227→### Storage\n   228→\n   229→Metadata in the store (SQLite initially). Git refs serve as pointers to actual file\n   230→states — no duplication of file content.\n   231→\n   232→## MVP Scope (v0.1)\n   233→\n   234→### In Scope\n   235→\n   236→- `cloche` CLI: `run`, `status`, `logs`, `stop`\n   237→- `cloched` daemon: container lifecycle, status collection, gRPC API, SQLite store\n   238→- `cloche-agent`: DSL parser, graph engine, agent/script execution, status reporting\n   239→- Workflow DSL: steps, results, wiring, `done`/`abort` terminals, `file()` references\n   240→- Container model: Docker, copy-in project files, git push for extraction, network allowlist\n   241→- Agent adapters: Generic (run a command) + Claude Code\n   242→- Capture system: Record step inputs/outputs/results\n   243→\n   244→### Post-MVP\n   245→\n   246→- Self-evolution: failure pattern analysis, automatic step injection into workflows\n   247→- Replay system: partial/full/dry replay of captured runs\n   248→- Auto-split commits into stacked branches\n   249→- Additional agent adapters\n   250→- Alternative storage backends (Postgres, DynamoDB)\n   251→- Alternative container runtimes (Podman, Firecracker)\n   252→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01H2TvBVQzYEZLZT535z7eqf","session_id":"5888bf68-422b-4315-97ee-07c9cf3aacfd","uuid":"76135a83-9c20-48d6-966f-07c2179b0662"}
[2026-03-13T19:20:33Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_019x5XjCDxncT8udAeAsAD6S","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Workflows\n     2→\n     3→Cloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n     4→\n     5→## Workflow Locations\n     6→\n     7→Cloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n     8→\n     9→**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) — Run inside a Docker\n    10→container via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\n    11→standard workflows for coding tasks.\n    12→\n    13→**Host workflows** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) — Run on the host machine as the daemon\n    14→process. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\n    15→dispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\n    16→point for custom orchestration strategies.\n    17→\n    18→A single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\n    19→uses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n    20→\n    21→| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n    22→|-------|--------------|---------|\n    23→| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n    24→| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n    25→| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n    26→\n    27→Only `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a legacy\n    28→single-function mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n    29→\n    30→The `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\n    31→object with the following fields:\n    32→\n    33→| Field | Required | Description |\n    34→|-------|----------|-------------|\n    35→| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n    36→| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n    37→| `title` | no | Short summary |\n    38→| `description` | no | Full description |\n    39→| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n    40→\n    41→The daemon picks the first task with status `open` (or empty, for backward\n    42→compatibility), runs `main` with that task ID, then runs `finalize` with the outcome.\n    43→Tasks are deduplicated within a configurable timeout window to prevent rapid\n    44→reassignment.\n    45→\n    46→The convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\n    47→file is a parse error.\n    48→\n    49→## Concepts\n    50→\n    51→| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    52→|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    53→| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    54→| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n    55→| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n    56→| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step, with optional output mappings |\n    57→| done     | Built-in terminal step — successful completion                     |\n    58→| abort    | Built-in terminal step — failure with error reporting              |\n    59→\n    60→## Step Types\n    61→\n    62→Step type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n    63→\n    64→**agent** (has `prompt`) — Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\n    65→to the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\n    66→container. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    67→\n    68→**script** (has `run`) — Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\n    69→any deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    70→\n    71→**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) — Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\n    72→until it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n    73→\n    74→A step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\n    75→parse error.\n    76→\n    77→## DSL Syntax\n    78→\n    79→```\n    80→workflow \"develop\" {\n    81→  container {\n    82→    image = \"my-project:latest\"\n    83→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n    84→  }\n    85→\n    86→  step implement {\n    87→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    88→    results = [success, fail]\n    89→  }\n    90→\n    91→  step test {\n    92→    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    93→    results = [success, fail]\n    94→  }\n    95→\n    96→  step fix {\n    97→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n    98→    max_attempts = \"3\"\n    99→    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   100→  }\n   101→\n   102→  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step [optional output mappings]\n   103→  implement:success -> test\n   104→  implement:fail    -> abort\n   105→  test:success      -> done\n   106→  test:fail         -> fix\n   107→  fix:success       -> test\n   108→  fix:fail          -> abort\n   109→  fix:give-up       -> abort\n   110→}\n   111→```\n   112→\n   113→## Key Properties\n   114→\n   115→**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\n   116→field makes it a script step.\n   117→\n   118→**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\n   119→report. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n   120→\n   121→**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\n   122→existing ones by rewiring — without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\n   123→Cloche's self-evolution feature.\n   124→\n   125→**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\n   126→wired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n   127→\n   128→## Wire Output Mappings\n   129→\n   130→Wires can include output mappings that extract values from a step's output and inject\n   131→them as environment variables into the target step:\n   132→\n   133→```\n   134→step-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n   135→```\n   136→\n   137→The general form:\n   138→\n   139→```\n   140→FROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n   141→```\n   142→\n   143→Where `KEY` is the environment variable name and `EXPR` is an output path expression\n   144→starting with the contextual keyword `output`:\n   145→\n   146→| Expression | Meaning |\n   147→|---|---|\n   148→| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n   149→| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n   150→| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n   151→| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n   152→| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n   153→\n   154→If the source step's output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the parsed\n   155→structure. If the output is plain text, only bare `output` is valid. The resolved\n   156→value is converted to a string for env var injection.\n   157→\n   158→If two wires targeting the same step both map the same env var key, validation\n   159→returns an error (the mapping would be ambiguous). The same key may be used on\n   160→wires to different steps without conflict.\n   161→\n   162→## Workflow-Level Configuration Blocks\n   163→\n   164→Workflows support a configuration block at the workflow level to set defaults for all\n   165→steps. The block name depends on the workflow location:\n   166→\n   167→**`container {}`** — For container workflows. Sets container image, agent command, and\n   168→network allowlist.\n   169→\n   170→```\n   171→workflow \"develop\" {\n   172→  container {\n   173→    image = \"my-project:latest\"\n   174→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   175→    agent_args = \"-p --dangerously-skip-permissions\"\n   176→  }\n   177→  ...\n   178→}\n   179→```\n   180→\n   181→Supported keys: `image`, `agent_command`, `agent_args`, `network_allow`.\n   182→\n   183→**`host {}`** — For host workflows (`host.cloche`). Sets agent defaults for agent steps\n   184→running on the host machine.\n   185→\n   186→```\n   187→workflow \"main\" {\n   188→  host {\n   189→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   190→  }\n   191→  ...\n   192→}\n   193→```\n   194→\n   195→Supported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`.\n   196→\n   197→Step-level `agent_command` and `agent_args` override workflow-level defaults. The\n   198→resolution order is: step-level > workflow-level block > `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` env\n   199→var > default `claude`.\n   200→\n   201→## Host Workflow Example\n   202→\n   203→A three-phase `host.cloche` with separate `list-tasks`, `main`, and `finalize`\n   204→workflows:\n   205→\n   206→```\n   207→# .cloche/host.cloche — runs on the host machine\n   208→\n   209→workflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   210→  step fetch-tickets {\n   211→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   212→    results = [success, fail]\n   213→  }\n   214→\n   215→  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n   216→  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n   217→}\n   218→\n   219→workflow \"main\" {\n   220→  host {\n   221→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   222→  }\n   223→\n   224→  step prepare-prompt {\n   225→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   226→    results = [success, fail]\n   227→  }\n   228→\n   229→  step develop {\n   230→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   231→    results       = [success, fail]\n   232→  }\n   233→\n   234→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   235→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   236→  develop:success        -> done\n   237→  develop:fail           -> done\n   238→}\n   239→\n   240→workflow \"finalize\" {\n   241→  step push-for-review {\n   242→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n   243→    results = [success, fail]\n   244→  }\n   245→\n   246→  push-for-review:success -> done\n   247→  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n   248→}\n   249→```\n   250→\n   251→The daemon runs `list-tasks` to discover work (output is JSONL), picks an open task,\n   252→runs `main` with `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` set, then runs `finalize` regardless of outcome.\n   253→The `list-tasks` script writes one JSON object per line to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`.\n   254→The `main` workflow receives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket.\n   255→The `finalize` workflow decides what to do based on the outcome (available via\n   256→`CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars).\n   257→\n   258→## Execution Model\n   259→\n   260→**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\n   261→container. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\n   262→wiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\n   263→All steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n   264→\n   265→**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. A single\n   266→`host.cloche` file may contain multiple named workflows; the daemon orchestrates them\n   267→in three phases (list-tasks → main → finalize). Script steps run via `sh -c` with the\n   268→working directory set to the **main git worktree** (i.e. the main branch checkout), even\n   269→if the project directory is a linked worktree on a different branch. This ensures\n   270→host-workflow scripts from main are used for all runs. Workflow steps dispatch container\n   271→runs via the daemon's standard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`,\n   272→`CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`, etc.) are injected into each step; `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` still\n   273→points to the actual project directory.\n   274→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01H2TvBVQzYEZLZT535z7eqf","session_id":"5888bf68-422b-4315-97ee-07c9cf3aacfd","uuid":"16e0c7d4-d5cd-4c1a-9c6a-4047219625cd"}
