[2026-03-13T19:20:33Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01554X1ErHQ3vJZpWLW8phHv","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Cloche Usage\n     2→\n     3→Cloche runs containerized workflows for autonomous coding agents. You define a\n     4→workflow graph in the `.cloche` DSL, Cloche copies your project into a Docker\n     5→container, runs the workflow steps (agent prompts and shell scripts), and extracts\n     6→results to a git branch.\n     7→\n     8→## Core Concepts\n     9→\n    10→- **Workflow**: A directed graph of steps connected by named-result wiring.\n    11→- **Step**: A unit of work. Type is inferred: `prompt` = agent step, `run` = script step, `workflow_name` = workflow step (host only).\n    12→- **Result**: A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. `success`, `fail`, `needs-research`). Steps declare their possible results; the engine follows wiring based on the reported result.\n    13→- **Wiring**: Maps `step:result` pairs to the next step. Separate from step definitions.\n    14→- **Terminals**: `done` (success) and `abort` (failure) are built-in terminal targets.\n    15→\n    16→## Workflow DSL\n    17→\n    18→Workflow files use the `.cloche` extension and live in `.cloche/`. The first step\n    19→declared is the entry point. Graphs are validated at parse time (all results wired,\n    20→no orphans, entry point exists).\n    21→\n    22→### Minimal Example\n    23→\n    24→```\n    25→workflow \"develop\" {\n    26→  step implement {\n    27→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    28→    results = [success, fail]\n    29→  }\n    30→\n    31→  step test {\n    32→    run = \"make test 2>&1\"\n    33→    results = [success, fail]\n    34→  }\n    35→\n    36→  implement:success -> test\n    37→  implement:fail -> abort\n    38→  test:success -> done\n    39→  test:fail -> abort\n    40→}\n    41→```\n    42→\n    43→### Step Configuration\n    44→\n    45→| Key | Type | Description |\n    46→|-----|------|-------------|\n    47→| `prompt` | string or `file(\"path\")` | Prompt template. Makes this an agent step. |\n    48→| `run` | string | Shell command. Makes this a script step. |\n    49→| `workflow_name` | string | Container workflow to dispatch. Makes this a workflow step (host only). |\n    50→| `results` | ident list | Declared result names, e.g. `[success, fail, give-up]`. |\n    51→| `max_attempts` | string | Max retries before automatic `give-up` result, e.g. `\"2\"`. |\n    52→| `timeout` | string | Step timeout as Go duration, e.g. `\"30m\"`, `\"2h\"`. Default: 30m. |\n    53→| `agent_command` | string | Agent binary name(s), comma-separated for fallback chains, e.g. `\"claude,gemini\"`. |\n    54→| `agent_args` | string | Override default agent arguments. |\n    55→| `feedback` | string | Set to `\"true\"` to include `.cloche/output/*.log` content in the prompt. |\n    56→| `prompt_step` | string | For workflow steps: which preceding step's output to use as the prompt. |\n    57→\n    58→A step must have exactly one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`.\n    59→\n    60→### The `file()` Function\n    61→\n    62→`file(\"path\")` reads the file at the given path relative to the working directory\n    63→(`/workspace/` in containers) at execution time, not parse time. Use it for prompt\n    64→templates:\n    65→\n    66→```\n    67→prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    68→```\n    69→\n    70→### The `container {}` Block\n    71→\n    72→Can appear at step level or workflow level. Keys are stored with a `container.` prefix.\n    73→\n    74→**Step level** — per-step container config:\n    75→```\n    76→step code {\n    77→  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    78→  container {\n    79→    image         = \"custom-agent:v2\"\n    80→    memory        = \"4g\"\n    81→    network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\", \"api.example.com\"]\n    82→  }\n    83→  results = [success, fail]\n    84→}\n    85→```\n    86→\n    87→**Workflow level** — defaults for all steps:\n    88→```\n    89→workflow \"develop\" {\n    90→  container {\n    91→    agent_command = \"gemini\"\n    92→    image         = \"myregistry/myimage:v2\"\n    93→    memory        = \"4g\"\n    94→  }\n    95→  ...\n    96→}\n    97→```\n    98→\n    99→Supported keys: `image`, `memory`, `network_allow`, `agent_command`, `agent_args`.\n   100→\n   101→### The `host {}` Block\n   102→\n   103→Can appear at workflow level in host workflows (`.cloche/host.cloche`). Keys are stored\n   104→with a `host.` prefix. Configures agent defaults for agent steps running on the host.\n   105→\n   106→```\n   107→workflow \"main\" {\n   108→  host {\n   109→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   110→  }\n   111→  ...\n   112→}\n   113→```\n   114→\n   115→Supported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`. Step-level `agent_command` and\n   116→`agent_args` config keys override the workflow-level `host {}` defaults.\n   117→\n   118→### Wiring Syntax\n   119→\n   120→Connect steps with `step:result -> next_step`:\n   121→\n   122→```\n   123→implement:success -> test\n   124→implement:fail -> abort\n   125→test:success -> done\n   126→test:fail -> fix\n   127→```\n   128→\n   129→### Wire Output Mappings\n   130→\n   131→Extract values from a step's JSON output and inject as env vars into the target:\n   132→\n   133→```\n   134→step-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n   135→```\n   136→\n   137→Path expressions:\n   138→\n   139→| Expression | Meaning |\n   140→|---|---|\n   141→| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n   142→| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n   143→| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n   144→| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n   145→| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n   146→\n   147→If the output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the structure. If it's plain\n   148→text, only bare `output` works.\n   149→\n   150→### Retry Loops\n   151→\n   152→Wire failures back to earlier steps:\n   153→\n   154→```\n   155→test:fail -> fix\n   156→fix:success -> test    // retry the test\n   157→fix:fail -> abort\n   158→```\n   159→\n   160→Use `max_attempts` to cap retries. When exhausted, the step returns `give-up`:\n   161→\n   162→```\n   163→step fix {\n   164→  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n   165→  max_attempts = \"2\"\n   166→  results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   167→}\n   168→```\n   169→\n   170→### Parallel Branches (Fanout)\n   171→\n   172→Wire one result to multiple targets for concurrent execution:\n   173→\n   174→```\n   175→test:success -> lint\n   176→test:success -> quality\n   177→```\n   178→\n   179→### Collect (Join)\n   180→\n   181→Synchronize parallel branches:\n   182→\n   183→```\n   184→collect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   185→collect any(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   186→```\n   187→\n   188→`all` fires when every condition is met. `any` fires when at least one is.\n   189→\n   190→### Comments\n   191→\n   192→Line comments with `//`:\n   193→\n   194→```\n   195→// This is a comment\n   196→implement:success -> test  // inline comment\n   197→```\n   198→\n   199→## Result Protocol\n   200→\n   201→Steps report results by printing a marker line to stdout:\n   202→\n   203→```\n   204→CLOCHE_RESULT:<name>\n   205→```\n   206→\n   207→For example: `CLOCHE_RESULT:success`, `CLOCHE_RESULT:needs-research`, `CLOCHE_RESULT:give-up`.\n   208→\n   209→Rules:\n   210→- The **last** `CLOCHE_RESULT:` line wins if multiple are printed.\n   211→- Marker lines are **stripped** from captured output (not passed to logs or downstream steps).\n   212→- The result name must match one of the step's declared `results`.\n   213→- For script steps with no marker: exit 0 = `success`, exit non-zero = `fail`.\n   214→- For agent steps: if exit non-zero with a marker, the marker result is used. If exit non-zero without a marker, falls back to the next agent in the fallback chain (or returns `fail` if last).\n   215→\n   216→## Prompt Assembly\n   217→\n   218→When an agent step runs, Cloche assembles a prompt from these sections (joined by blank lines):\n   219→\n   220→1. **Step template**: The step's `prompt` content (inline string or resolved `file(\"path\")`).\n   221→2. **User request**: Content of `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt` (set via `--prompt` flag), prefixed with `## User Request`.\n   222→3. **Validation output** (opt-in): If `feedback = \"true\"`, reads all `.log` files from `.cloche/output/` and includes them prefixed with `## Validation Output`.\n   223→4. **Result selection**: Lists the step's declared results with instructions to print exactly one `CLOCHE_RESULT:<name>` marker.\n   224→\n   225→The assembled prompt is passed to the agent command via stdin.\n   226→\n   227→## Agent Command Resolution\n   228→\n   229→Priority (highest to lowest):\n   230→1. Step-level `agent_command`\n   231→2. Workflow-level config block (`container { agent_command }` for container workflows, `host { agent_command }` for host workflows)\n   232→3. `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` environment variable\n   233→4. Default: `claude`\n   234→\n   235→### Fallback Chains\n   236→\n   237→Comma-separated commands are tried in order:\n   238→\n   239→```\n   240→agent_command = \"claude,gemini,codex\"\n   241→```\n   242→\n   243→- **Command not found / failed to start** — try next command\n   244→- **Exit non-zero without `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** — try next command\n   245→- **Exit non-zero with `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** — use that result (no fallback)\n   246→- **Exit 0** — use result (no fallback)\n   247→- **All commands fail to start** — step returns an error\n   248→- **Last command crashes without marker** — step returns `fail`\n   249→\n   250→Known agents (e.g. `claude`) get default arguments (`-p --output-format stream-json --verbose --dangerously-skip-permissions`). Unknown agents receive the prompt on stdin with no flags. Override with `agent_args`.\n   251→\n   252→### Agent Setup Guides\n   253→\n   254→For detailed container setup instructions per agent:\n   255→\n   256→- [How to set up Claude Code](agent-setup-claude.md) — session-based auth, no API key needed\n   257→- [How to set up Codex](agent-setup-codex.md) — API key configuration\n   258→\n   259→## Workflow Locations\n   260→\n   261→**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) run inside Docker\n   262→via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type.\n   263→\n   264→**Host workflow** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) runs on the host machine as the daemon.\n   265→Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow_name` step type\n   266→dispatches a container workflow run and blocks until it completes. Script steps\n   267→execute with their working directory set to the main git worktree, so host-workflow\n   268→fixes on main are available to in-flight runs even if they branched earlier.\n   269→\n   270→A single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\n   271→uses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n   272→\n   273→| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n   274→|-------|--------------|---------|\n   275→| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n   276→| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n   277→| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n   278→\n   279→Only `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a single-workflow\n   280→mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n   281→\n   282→### list-tasks Output Format\n   283→\n   284→The `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\n   285→object:\n   286→\n   287→| Field | Required | Description |\n   288→|-------|----------|-------------|\n   289→| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n   290→| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n   291→| `title` | no | Short summary |\n   292→| `description` | no | Full description |\n   293→| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n   294→\n   295→The daemon picks the first task with status `open`, runs `main` with that task's ID\n   296→set in `CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, then runs `finalize` with the outcome. Tasks are\n   297→deduplicated within a timeout window to prevent rapid reassignment of the same task.\n   298→\n   299→### Host Workflow Example\n   300→\n   301→A three-phase `host.cloche`:\n   302→\n   303→```\n   304→workflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   305→  step fetch-tickets {\n   306→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   307→    results = [success, fail]\n   308→  }\n   309→\n   310→  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n   311→  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n   312→}\n   313→\n   314→workflow \"main\" {\n   315→  host {\n   316→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   317→  }\n   318→\n   319→  step prepare-prompt {\n   320→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   321→    results = [success, fail]\n   322→  }\n   323→\n   324→  step develop {\n   325→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   326→    results       = [success, fail]\n   327→  }\n   328→\n   329→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   330→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   331→  develop:success        -> done\n   332→  develop:fail           -> done\n   333→}\n   334→\n   335→workflow \"finalize\" {\n   336→  step push-for-review {\n   337→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n   338→    results = [success, fail]\n   339→  }\n   340→\n   341→  push-for-review:success -> done\n   342→  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n   343→}\n   344→```\n   345→\n   346→The `list-tasks` script writes JSONL to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`. The `main` workflow\n   347→receives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket. The `finalize`\n   348→workflow receives `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars to decide\n   349→what cleanup to perform.\n   350→\n   351→### Host Step Environment Variables\n   352→\n   353→| Variable | Description |\n   354→|----------|-------------|\n   355→| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Absolute path to the project directory on the host. |\n   356→| `CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT` | Path where this step should write its output (for output mappings). |\n   357→| `CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT` | Path to the output file from the immediately preceding step. |\n   358→| `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` | The run ID for this workflow execution. |\n   359→| `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` | Task ID assigned by the daemon (set for `main` and `finalize` phases). |\n   360→| `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` | Result of the `main` workflow (`succeeded` or `failed`). Set for `finalize` phase only. |\n   361→| `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` | Run ID of the completed `main` workflow. Set for `finalize` phase only. |\n   362→| Wire-mapped vars | Any env vars declared in wire output mappings. |\n   363→\n   364→### Container Environment Variables\n   365→\n   366→| Variable | Description |\n   367→|----------|-------------|\n   368→| `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` | The run ID for this workflow execution. |\n   369→| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Working directory (set for script steps so `cloche get`/`cloche set` work). |\n   370→| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | Passed through from the host if set. |\n   371→| `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` | Overrides the default agent command inside the container. |\n   372→\n   373→## Setting Up Host Workflows\n   374→\n   375→The `host.cloche` file is the orchestration layer that ties everything together.\n   376→When you run `cloche init`, a minimal `host.cloche` with just a `main` workflow is\n   377→generated. As your project grows, you can add `list-tasks` and `finalize` workflows\n   378→to automate task discovery and cleanup.\n   379→\n   380→The daemon recognizes three workflow names in `host.cloche` and runs them in order:\n   381→\n   382→1. **`list-tasks`** — discover available work\n   383→2. **`main`** — execute the work\n   384→3. **`finalize`** — clean up after the work completes\n   385→\n   386→All three workflows live in the same `.cloche/host.cloche` file. Only `main` is\n   387→required; `list-tasks` and `finalize` are optional.\n   388→\n   389→### `list-tasks` — Discovering Work\n   390→\n   391→The `list-tasks` workflow runs first. Its job is to query your task tracker (issue\n   392→tracker, project board, ticket queue, etc.) and output a list of available tasks.\n   393→\n   394→**When it runs:** The daemon calls `list-tasks` at the start of each orchestration\n   395→loop iteration, before launching any new `main` runs.\n   396→\n   397→**Output format:** The final step must write JSONL (one JSON object per line) to\n   398→`$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`. Each line represents a task:\n   399→\n   400→```json\n   401→{\"id\": \"PROJ-42\", \"status\": \"open\", \"title\": \"Fix login bug\", \"description\": \"Users report...\"}\n   402→{\"id\": \"PROJ-43\", \"status\": \"in-progress\", \"title\": \"Add caching\", \"description\": \"...\"}\n   403→{\"id\": \"PROJ-44\", \"status\": \"open\", \"title\": \"Update docs\", \"description\": \"...\"}\n   404→```\n   405→\n   406→The daemon picks the first task with `status: \"open\"` and passes it to `main`.\n   407→Tasks that were recently assigned are deduplicated within a timeout window (default\n   408→5 minutes) to prevent the same task from being picked repeatedly.\n   409→\n   410→**How to configure:** Write a script that queries your task source and outputs JSONL:\n   411→\n   412→```\n   413→workflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   414→  step fetch-tickets {\n   415→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   416→    results = [success, fail]\n   417→  }\n   418→\n   419→  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n   420→  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n   421→}\n   422→```\n   423→\n   424→**If omitted:** The daemon falls back to single-workflow mode — it runs `main`\n   425→once without task assignment. This is fine for simple use cases where you trigger\n   426→runs manually with `cloche run`.\n   427→\n   428→### `main` — Executing Work\n   429→\n   430→The `main` workflow does the actual work. This is the only required workflow in\n   431→`host.cloche` and is always generated by `cloche init`.\n   432→\n   433→**When it runs:** After `list-tasks` selects a task (or immediately if `list-tasks`\n   434→is absent). The daemon sets the `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` environment variable from the\n   435→selected task.\n   436→\n   437→**How to configure:** A typical `main` workflow prepares a prompt from the task data,\n   438→then dispatches a container workflow:\n   439→\n   440→```\n   441→workflow \"main\" {\n   442→  host {\n   443→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   444→  }\n   445→\n   446→  step prepare-prompt {\n   447→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   448→    results = [success, fail]\n   449→  }\n   450→\n   451→  step develop {\n   452→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   453→    prompt_step   = \"prepare-prompt\"\n   454→    results       = [success, fail]\n   455→  }\n   456→\n   457→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   458→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   459→  develop:success        -> done\n   460→  develop:fail           -> done\n   461→}\n   462→```\n   463→\n   464→The `workflow_name` step type dispatches a container workflow run and blocks until\n   465→it completes. Use `prompt_step` to specify which preceding step's output should be\n   466→used as the prompt for the container run.\n   467→\n   468→You can add steps before or after the container workflow — for example, a\n   469→`claim-task` step to mark the task as in-progress in your tracker, or a\n   470→`merge-to-main` step to merge the result branch.\n   471→\n   472→### `finalize` — Post-Run Cleanup\n   473→\n   474→The `finalize` workflow handles cleanup after `main` completes. It runs regardless\n   475→of whether `main` succeeded or failed.\n   476→\n   477→**When it runs:** Immediately after `main` finishes (success or failure). The daemon\n   478→sets two additional environment variables:\n   479→\n   480→- `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` — `\"succeeded\"` or `\"failed\"`\n   481→- `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` — the run ID of the completed `main` workflow\n   482→\n   483→**How to configure:** Use the outcome to decide what cleanup to perform:\n   484→\n   485→```\n   486→workflow \"finalize\" {\n   487→  step close-task {\n   488→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/close-task.sh\"\n   489→    results = [success, fail]\n   490→  }\n   491→\n   492→  close-task:success -> done\n   493→  close-task:fail    -> done\n   494→}\n   495→```\n   496→\n   497→A typical `finalize` script checks `$CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and acts accordingly —\n   498→closing the ticket on success, or posting a failure comment for investigation.\n   499→Wiring both results to `done` (not `abort`) ensures the daemon treats the\n   500→finalize phase as complete regardless of the cleanup script's exit status.\n   501→\n   502→**If omitted:** The daemon skips the finalize phase entirely. This is fine if you\n   503→don't need automated cleanup.\n   504→\n   505→### Putting It All Together\n   506→\n   507→The three-phase model enables fully automated task pipelines:\n   508→\n   509→1. The orchestration loop calls `list-tasks` to find open work\n   510→2. It picks an open task and launches `main` with the task context\n   511→3. `main` prepares a prompt, dispatches a container workflow, and optionally merges results\n   512→4. `finalize` closes the ticket or reports failure\n   513→5. The loop repeats, picking the next open task\n   514→\n   515→Start the loop with `cloche loop` and monitor tasks with `cloche tasks`. The\n   516→`--max` flag controls how many `main` runs execute concurrently.\n   517→\n   518→## Complete Example: Container Workflow with Parallel Validation\n   519→\n   520→```\n   521→workflow \"develop\" {\n   522→  step implement {\n   523→    prompt = file(\"prompts/implement.md\")\n   524→    results = [success, fail]\n   525→  }\n   526→\n   527→  step test {\n   528→    run = \"bundle exec rake test 2>&1\"\n   529→    results = [success, fail]\n   530→  }\n   531→\n   532→  step lint {\n   533→    run = \"bundle exec rubocop 2>&1\"\n   534→    results = [success, fail]\n   535→  }\n   536→\n   537→  step quality {\n   538→    run = \"python3 scripts/quality-check.py 2>&1\"\n   539→    results = [success, fail]\n   540→  }\n   541→\n   542→  step fix {\n   543→    prompt = file(\"prompts/fix.md\")\n   544→    max_attempts = \"2\"\n   545→    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   546→  }\n   547→\n   548→  implement:success -> test\n   549→  implement:fail -> abort\n   550→\n   551→  test:success -> lint\n   552→  test:success -> quality\n   553→  test:fail -> fix\n   554→\n   555→  lint:fail -> fix\n   556→  quality:fail -> fix\n   557→  collect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   558→\n   559→  fix:success -> test\n   560→  fix:fail -> abort\n   561→  fix:give-up -> abort\n   562→}\n   563→```\n   564→\n   565→## Container Isolation Model\n   566→\n   567→- **Files in**: `docker cp` copies the project into `/workspace/`. No bind mounts. Override files from `.cloche/overrides/` are applied on top. `.git/` is included.\n   568→- **Files out**: On completion, the daemon extracts results via `docker cp` into a git worktree and commits to a `cloche/<run-id>` branch.\n   569→- **Auth files**: `~/.claude/` and `~/.claude.json` are copied into each container at `/home/agent/` for Claude Code session reuse. Copied (not bind-mounted) so each container gets its own isolated copy.\n   570→- **Network**: Containers have network access (needed for API calls).\n   571→- **Cleanup**: Containers are removed after successful runs unless `--keep-container` is set. Failed runs always keep their container.\n   572→\n   573→Your project directory is never modified by the container.\n   574→\n   575→## CLI Reference\n   576→\n   577→Every subcommand supports `--help` (or `-h`) to show detailed usage, flags, and\n   578→examples. Use `cloche help <command>` for the same output:\n   579→\n   580→```\n   581→cloche --help              # top-level overview\n   582→cloche help run            # detailed help for \"run\"\n   583→cloche run --help          # same as above\n   584→```\n   585→\n   586→### `cloche init`\n   587→\n   588→Scaffold a new Cloche project.\n   589→\n   590→```\n   591→cloche init [--workflow <name>] [--base-image <base>]\n   592→```\n   593→\n   594→| Flag | Default | Description |\n   595→|------|---------|-------------|\n   596→| `--workflow <name>` | `develop` | Workflow name. Creates `.cloche/<name>.cloche`. |\n   597→| `--base-image <base>` | `cloche-base:latest` | Base Docker image for the generated Dockerfile. |\n   598→\n   599→Creates `.cloche/` with workflow file, Dockerfile, `config.toml`, prompt templates,\n   600→host workflow (`host.cloche`), and prompt generation script. Skips existing files.\n   601→\n   602→### `cloche run`\n   603→\n   604→Launch a workflow run.\n   605→\n   606→```\n   607→cloche run --workflow <name> [--prompt \"...\"] [--title \"...\"] [--keep-container]\n   608→```\n   609→\n   610→| Flag | Description |\n   611→|------|-------------|\n   612→| `--workflow <name>` | Workflow name. Resolves to `.cloche/<name>.cloche`. |\n   613→| `--prompt \"...\"`, `-p` | Inline prompt written to `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt`. |\n   614→| `--title \"...\"` | One-line summary for status display. Auto-generated if omitted. |\n   615→| `--keep-container` | Keep container on success (failed runs always keep it). |\n   616→\n   617→Must be run from inside a git repository. The daemon auto-rebuilds the Docker image\n   618→when `.cloche/Dockerfile` changes.\n   619→\n   620→### `cloche status`\n   621→\n   622→```\n   623→cloche status <run-id>\n   624→```\n   625→\n   626→Shows run title, type (`host`/`container`), state, active steps, and per-step results.\n   627→\n   628→### `cloche list`\n   629→\n   630→```\n   631→cloche list [flags]\n   632→```\n   633→\n   634→Lists runs for the current project directory. Pass `--all` to show runs across all projects.\n   635→Results can be filtered by state, project, issue, or limited to a fixed number.\n   636→\n   637→| Flag | Description |\n   638→|------|-------------|\n   639→| `--all` | Show runs from all projects (default: current project only). |\n   640→| `--project, -p DIR` | Filter by project directory. |\n   641→| `--state, -s STATE` | Filter by run state (`pending`, `running`, `succeeded`, `failed`, `cancelled`). |\n   642→| `--limit, -n NUM` | Limit the number of results returned. |\n   643→| `--issue, -i ID` | Filter by issue/task ID. |\n   644→\n   645→### `cloche logs`\n   646→\n   647→```\n   648→cloche logs <run-id> [--step <name>] [--type <full|script|llm>] [-f]\n   649→```\n   650→\n   651→| Flag | Description |\n   652→|------|-------------|\n   653→| `--step <name>` | Show only logs for the specified step. |\n   654→| `--type <full\\|script\\|llm>` | Log type filter. |\n   655→| `-f` | Follow mode: display existing logs then continue streaming new lines as they arrive (like `tail -f`). |\n   656→\n   657→Without `-f`, displays all logs captured to date and exits (even for active runs). With `-f` on an active run, existing logs are sent first, then new output is streamed in real time via gRPC until the run completes.\n   658→\n   659→### `cloche poll`\n   660→\n   661→```\n   662→cloche poll <run-id>\n   663→```\n   664→\n   665→Block until the run finishes. Polls every 2 seconds. Exits 0 on success, 1 on failure.\n   666→\n   667→### `cloche stop`\n   668→\n   669→```\n   670→cloche stop <run-id>\n   671→```\n   672→\n   673→### `cloche delete`\n   674→\n   675→```\n   676→cloche delete <container-or-run-id>\n   677→```\n   678→\n   679→Delete a retained Docker container by container ID or run ID.\n   680→\n   681→### `cloche health`\n   682→\n   683→```\n   684→cloche health\n   685→```\n   686→\n   687→Show per-project pass/fail summary. Requires `CLOCHE_HTTP`.\n   688→\n   689→### `cloche workflow`\n   690→\n   691→```\n   692→cloche workflow [--project <dir>]\n   693→cloche workflow <name> [--project <dir>]\n   694→```\n   695→\n   696→List all workflows or render a specific workflow as an ASCII-art graph.\n   697→\n   698→| Flag | Default | Description |\n   699→|------|---------|-------------|\n   700→| `--project <dir>`, `-p` | current directory | Project directory to search for workflows. |\n   701→\n   702→With no arguments, lists all workflows grouped by type (container or host). With a\n   703→workflow name, renders the workflow graph showing step boxes, wiring, and result paths.\n   704→Wires are colorized: green for `success`, red for `fail`/`failed`,\n   705→blue/yellow/orange/magenta for other results. Wires to the same destination are merged\n   706→for readability.\n   707→\n   708→### `cloche project`\n   709→\n   710→Show project info and config.\n   711→\n   712→```\n   713→cloche project [--name <label>]\n   714→```\n   715→\n   716→By default, looks up the project by the current working directory. Use `--name` to look\n   717→up a project by its registered label instead.\n   718→\n   719→| Flag | Default | Description |\n   720→|------|---------|-------------|\n   721→| `--name <label>` | _(cwd lookup)_ | Look up project by label (e.g. `cloche`) instead of directory. |\n   722→\n   723→Output includes: config settings (active, concurrency, stagger, dedup, evolution),\n   724→orchestrator loop state (running/stopped), currently active runs, and known container\n   725→and host workflow names.\n   726→\n   727→### `cloche get`\n   728→\n   729→```\n   730→cloche get <key>\n   731→```\n   732→\n   733→Get a value from the run context store (`.cloche/<run-id>/context.json`). Requires\n   734→the `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` environment variable. Uses `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` if set, otherwise\n   735→the current working directory. Exits 1 if the key is not found.\n   736→\n   737→### `cloche set`\n   738→\n   739→```\n   740→cloche set <key> <value|->\n   741→```\n   742→\n   743→Set a value in the run context store (`.cloche/<run-id>/context.json`). Requires\n   744→the `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` environment variable. Uses `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` if set, otherwise\n   745→the current working directory. Creates the file and directories if they don't exist.\n   746→Pass `-` as the value to read from stdin (trailing newlines are trimmed).\n   747→\n   748→### `cloche tasks`\n   749→\n   750→```\n   751→cloche tasks [--project <dir>]\n   752→```\n   753→\n   754→Show the task pipeline and assignment state for an orchestration loop. Displays\n   755→upcoming/open tasks, which tasks are assigned to which runs, and auto-assignment\n   756→state. Requires `CLOCHE_HTTP` (talks to the daemon's web API).\n   757→\n   758→| Flag | Default | Description |\n   759→|------|---------|-------------|\n   760→| `--project <dir>` | current directory name | Project to query tasks for. |\n   761→\n   762→### `cloche loop`\n   763→\n   764→Start or stop the daemon's orchestration loop. The loop automatically picks up\n   765→tasks from the pipeline and runs them.\n   766→\n   767→```\n   768→cloche loop [--max <n>]\n   769→cloche loop stop\n   770→```\n   771→\n   772→| Flag | Default | Description |\n   773→|------|---------|-------------|\n   774→| `--max <n>` | config value | Maximum concurrent runs. Defaults to the value in `.cloche/config.toml`. |\n   775→\n   776→`cloche loop stop` disables the loop. Running tasks are not cancelled.\n   777→\n   778→### `cloche shutdown`\n   779→\n   780→```\n   781→cloche shutdown\n   782→```\n   783→\n   784→## Project Layout\n   785→\n   786→```\n   787→my-project/\n   788→├── .cloche/\n   789→│   ├── develop.cloche        # Container workflow\n   790→│   ├── host.cloche           # Host orchestration workflow\n   791→│   ├── Dockerfile            # Container image definition\n   792→│   ├── config.toml           # Project configuration\n   793→│   ├── prompts/              # Prompt templates\n   794→│   │   ├── implement.md\n   795→│   │   ├── fix.md\n   796→│   │   └── update-docs.md\n   797→│   ├── scripts/              # Host-side scripts\n   798→│   ├── overrides/            # Files copied on top of /workspace/\n   799→│   │   └── CLAUDE.md         # Container-specific CLAUDE.md (optional)\n   800→│   └── <run-id>/             # Runtime state (gitignored)\n   801→│       ├── prompt.txt        # User prompt\n   802→│       ├── context.json      # Shared key-value store (cloche get/set)\n   803→│       ├── output/\n   804→│       │   ├── full.log      # Unified log\n   805→│       │   ├── test.log      # Per-step script output\n   806→│       │   └── llm-impl.log  # Per-step LLM conversation\n   807→│       ├── attempt_count/    # Retry counters for max_attempts\n   808→│       └── history.log       # Step execution log\n   809→├── src/                      # Project source (untouched by Cloche)\n   810→└── .git/\n   811→```\n   812→\n   813→## Daemon Configuration\n   814→\n   815→| Variable | Default | Description |\n   816→|----------|---------|-------------|\n   817→| `CLOCHE_LISTEN` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Listen address |\n   818→| `CLOCHE_DB` | `cloche.db` | SQLite database path |\n   819→| `CLOCHE_RUNTIME` | `docker` | `docker` or `local` (subprocess, for dev only) |\n   820→| `CLOCHE_IMAGE` | `cloche-agent:latest` | Default Docker image |\n   821→| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | _(unset)_ | HTTP address for web dashboard. Not started unless set. |\n   822→| `CLOCHE_AGENT_PATH` | _(auto)_ | Path to `cloche-agent` binary (local runtime) |\n   823→| `CLOCHE_LLM_COMMAND` | _(unset)_ | Command for LLM calls (evolution, merge conflicts) |\n   824→| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | _(unset)_ | Passed into Docker containers |\n   825→| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_MOUNTS` | _(unset)_ | Extra bind mounts (comma-separated `host:container`) |\n   826→| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` | _(unset)_ | Extra env vars (comma-separated `KEY=VALUE`) |\n   827→\n   828→### Client Configuration\n   829→\n   830→| Variable | Default | Description |\n   831→|----------|---------|-------------|\n   832→| `CLOCHE_ADDR` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Daemon gRPC address |\n   833→| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | `localhost:8080` | Daemon HTTP address |\n   834→\n   835→## Dockerfile Requirements\n   836→\n   837→The container image must have:\n   838→- `cloche-agent` binary at `/usr/local/bin/cloche-agent`\n   839→- `git` installed\n   840→- An `agent` user (cloche wraps commands with `chown` + `su agent`)\n   841→- `/workspace` as the working directory\n   842→- Your project's build dependencies and the agent binary (e.g. `claude`)\n   843→\n   844→## Build Commands\n   845→\n   846→```\n   847→make build          # Build all binaries to bin/\n   848→make test           # Run all tests\n   849→make test-short     # Run tests (skip slow ones)\n   850→make lint           # Run go vet\n   851→make proto          # Regenerate gRPC code from protobuf\n   852→make docker-build   # Build the cloche-agent Docker image\n   853→make install        # Build, install to ~/.local/bin/, restart daemon\n   854→make clean          # Remove bin/\n   855→```\n   856→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01H2TvBVQzYEZLZT535z7eqf","session_id":"5888bf68-422b-4315-97ee-07c9cf3aacfd","uuid":"5389bf49-d0dc-44e5-ab4d-1da7824fa243"}
[2026-03-13T19:20:33Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_015kGqv35Zo3huMdiWjcPb9T","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Installation\n     2→\n     3→This document covers the various ways to install Cloche on your machine.\n     4→\n     5→## Prerequisites\n     6→\n     7→All installation methods require:\n     8→\n     9→- **Docker** — Cloche runs workflows in containers\n    10→- **Git** — result extraction uses git worktrees\n    11→\n    12→## Build from Source\n    13→\n    14→Clone the repository, build the binaries and Docker image, and install them:\n    15→\n    16→```\n    17→git clone https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche.git\n    18→cd cloche\n    19→make install\n    20→```\n    21→\n    22→`make install` builds all three binaries (`cloche`, `cloched`, `cloche-agent`),\n    23→builds the `cloche-agent:latest` Docker image, installs the binaries to\n    24→`~/.local/bin/`, and starts the daemon. You can change the install prefix:\n    25→\n    26→```\n    27→make install PREFIX=/usr/local\n    28→```\n    29→\n    30→Make sure the install prefix is on your `PATH`:\n    31→\n    32→```\n    33→export PATH=\"$HOME/.local/bin:$PATH\"\n    34→```\n    35→\n    36→### Build Requirements\n    37→\n    38→- Go 1.25+\n    39→\n    40→## `go install`\n    41→\n    42→If you have Go installed, you can install the binaries directly:\n    43→\n    44→```\n    45→go install github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/cmd/cloche@latest\n    46→go install github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/cmd/cloched@latest\n    47→go install github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/cmd/cloche-agent@latest\n    48→```\n    49→\n    50→This places the binaries in `$GOPATH/bin` (or `$HOME/go/bin` by default).\n    51→\n    52→You still need to build the Docker image separately. Clone the repository and\n    53→run:\n    54→\n    55→```\n    56→git clone https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche.git\n    57→cd cloche\n    58→make docker-build\n    59→```\n    60→\n    61→## Pre-built Release Binaries (Planned)\n    62→\n    63→> **Note:** Pre-built release binaries are not yet available. This section\n    64→> describes the planned installation method for when releases are published.\n    65→\n    66→Download pre-built binaries from the\n    67→[GitHub Releases](https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/releases) page. Each\n    68→release will include archives for common platforms (Linux amd64, Linux arm64,\n    69→macOS amd64, macOS arm64).\n    70→\n    71→```\n    72→# Example: Linux amd64\n    73→curl -LO https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/releases/latest/download/cloche-linux-amd64.tar.gz\n    74→tar xzf cloche-linux-amd64.tar.gz\n    75→sudo install cloche cloched cloche-agent /usr/local/bin/\n    76→```\n    77→\n    78→You still need to build the Docker image. Clone the repo and run\n    79→`make docker-build`:\n    80→\n    81→```\n    82→git clone https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche.git\n    83→cd cloche\n    84→make docker-build\n    85→```\n    86→\n    87→## Homebrew (macOS / Linux) (Planned)\n    88→\n    89→> **Note:** A Homebrew tap is not yet published. This section describes the\n    90→> planned installation method.\n    91→\n    92→```\n    93→brew tap cloche-dev/tap\n    94→brew install cloche\n    95→```\n    96→\n    97→This will install all three binaries. You will still need the Docker image —\n    98→the formula will print post-install instructions for building or pulling it.\n    99→\n   100→## Verifying the Installation\n   101→\n   102→After installing, verify that everything works:\n   103→\n   104→```\n   105→# Check the binaries\n   106→cloche --help\n   107→cloched --help\n   108→\n   109→# Start the daemon (if not already running)\n   110→cloched &\n   111→\n   112→# Build the agent image\n   113→make docker-build\n   114→\n   115→# Run a quick test from any git repository with a .cloche/ directory\n   116→cloche list\n   117→```\n   118→\n   119→## Upgrading\n   120→\n   121→To upgrade an existing installation, repeat your original installation method.\n   122→If you built from source:\n   123→\n   124→```\n   125→cd cloche\n   126→git pull\n   127→make install\n   128→```\n   129→\n   130→The `make install` target stops the running daemon, installs the new binaries,\n   131→and restarts the daemon automatically.\n   132→\n   133→## Next Steps\n   134→\n   135→- [Usage guide](USAGE.md) — quick start, CLI reference, and workflow setup\n   136→- [Workflow DSL reference](workflows.md) — full syntax for `.cloche` files\n   137→- [How to set up Claude Code](agent-setup-claude.md) — container setup for Claude\n   138→- [How to set up Codex](agent-setup-codex.md) — container setup for Codex\n   139→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01H2TvBVQzYEZLZT535z7eqf","session_id":"5888bf68-422b-4315-97ee-07c9cf3aacfd","uuid":"ec4a8226-244a-47c3-8f0c-7f98ca6fc95c"}
